properties.Title: High Water Advisory Alert Is Being Issued For The Whiteshell Lakes Area
properties.Summary:
Description: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a High Water Advisory for the Whiteshell Lakes due to heavy rains across Manitoba and northwest Ontario. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as levels and flows are rising. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing water or waters of unknown depth. Follow all directions by the local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe.
Expires: 2019-10-12T16:00:00-05:00

Area: Whiteshell Lakes
properties.Author: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization

properties.Title: Wind Effect Alert Issued For The South Basins Of Lake Manitoba And Lake Winnipeg.
properties.Summary:
Description: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a high wind-effect warning for the south basin of Lake Manitoba, and for the shorelines near Gimli on the west side and Victoria Beach on the east side of Lake Winnipeg. High winds are expected to last until Saturday morning. Wind speed and wave action could raise water levels as much as five feet or more. Be watchful as these winds can result in significant and forceful wave action on shorelines. Property owners in the affected area should take all necessary precautions to stay safe.
Expires: 2019-10-12T12:00:00-05:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization, 2019-10-11T15:27:35-05:00, 883D2059-5752-9965-2E0F-7A0AE5D1B5B0
Area: South basin of Lake Winnipeg, and for the shorelines near Gimli on the west side and Victoria Beach on the east side of Lake Winnipeg.
properties.Author: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: As of early this morning much of southern Manitoba remains under a winter storm warning as a massive low pressure system continues to relentlessly pummel the area with heavy snow and strong winds. Widespread snowfall accumulations of 40-60 cm have been reported in much of western Manitoba and the western Red River Valley and many highways remain closed. Widespread power outages continue to plague the region with significant numbers of downed or damaged trees. The low pressure system will remain more or less stationary and hence snowfall and strong winds will continue, with further accumulations ranging from 5 to 15 cm over the course of the day. The snow will continue to be accompanied by winds gusting as high as 60 km/h giving near-zero visibility at times in blowing snow. Travelling will remain difficult if not impossible today as the heavy accumulating snow, strong winds, and temperatures near zero will result in treacherous conditions. Further downed trees and power outages are to be expected. The storm will begin to weaken tonight, although a few areas will still see another 5 cm or so accumulation by Sunday morning. The winter storm warning has been ended for Winnipeg as the worst of the system has now pushed west of the city. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected. Heavy snow will move into the southeastern corner of Saskatchewan late this evening as the edge of a major storm system brushes the area. Areas nearest the Manitoba border as well as higher terrain around Moose Mountain Provincial Park will see 10 to 15 cm before the snow tapers off late Saturday afternoon. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with gusty winds and visibility frequently near zero in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. A low pressure system moving across central Yukon tonight is producing snow and easterly winds of 80 km/h gusting 100 near the Richardson Mountains. Blizzard conditions with near zero visibility wil continue tonight. A further 5 to 10 cm will fall for a total accumulation of 10 to 15 cm. The very strong easterly winds will ease Saturday morning. The snow will ease near midday on Saturday. ### Travel is expected to be extremely hazardous due to reduced visibility. Road closures are possible. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.

properties.Title: Tropical Cyclone Information Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: For Sub-tropical Storm Melissa. A low pressure system well south of Cape Cod has evolved into Sub-Tropical Storm Melissa. This storm is forecast to track south of the Maritime marine district tonight, Saturday and Sunday. Gale to storm force easterly winds are forecast for the offshore marine areas south of Nova Scotia. Melissa will not affect land areas of Nova Scotia except for large waves and heavy pounding surf at the coast. Melissa is expected to weaken as it tracks eastward well south of Nova Scotia. Another area of low pressure forming north of Sub-Tropical Storm Melissa will give rainfall to the Maritimes tonight and Saturday. Over areas of southern Nova Scotia, 25 to 45 millimetres are forecast. A special weather statement was issued last night for the potential for significant rainfall associated with this low. This will be the only statement on Sub-Tropical Storm Melissa. Forecaster: Hatt ### Please continue to monitor alerts issued by the Canadian Hurricane Centre and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
Expires: 2019-10-13T01:25:13-00:00

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: An extreme winter storm will continue to pummel parts of southern Manitoba into the weekend as a Colorado Low stalls over the area. The most intense winter storm conditions continue tonight for areas north and west of the Red River Valley. The western half of the Red River Valley will be hit with an extraordinary amount of snow; 30 to 50 cm has been reported as of 8 pm CDT, and up to an additional 10-20 cm is expected tonight before finally tapering off by morning. Heavy snow has moved into the western Parklands and Interlake areas, where 30 to 50 cm is expected by late Saturday. Very strong winds will accompany the heavy snow, with gusts to 80 km/h continuing through Saturday as well. Stronger gusts of 100 km/h will be possible off of Lake Manitoba, the north basin of Lake Winnipeg, and in wind prone areas of the Riding Mountains. To the east of the the Red River, precipitation has tapered off and the Winter Storm Watch has now been ended. For the City of Winnipeg, up to an additional 2-4 cm of heavy snow is expected tonight before tapering off late overnight. The strong winds will also steadily diminish tonight for these areas. Travelling will remain difficult if not impossible into Saturday as the heavy accumulating snow, strong winds, and temperatures near zero result in treacherous conditions. The combination of heavy, wet snow and strong winds will likely result in more downed trees and power lines. This storm system will gradually weaken through the day on Saturday, and significant accumulations are not expected anywhere in southern Manitoba beyond Saturday night. ### Road closures are possible. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-12T17:37:50-00:00

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain and strong winds continuing over eastern regions today. Rain will taper off in the west this morning and this afternoon or this evening in the east. Total rainfall amounts of 20 to 40 mm are expected, with the highest amounts over eastern portions of the province. Rough and pounding surf will continue to impact parts of the Atlantic coast today. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
